Introduction

Video games have emerged as a new form of entertainment, with PC games being particularly popular. Steam, one of the most successful PC game distributors, provides public game metrics openly, including genre, publisher, and price. We want to analyze this data to see if there are specific factors that have a large impact on game sales.

Since video games are unique experiences, many believe that a game's success is independent of external features such as category or ratings. We plan to either validate or refute this claim by analyzing the accuracy of a predictive model.

This tutorial will guide you through the various steps and methodologies required to analyze a dataset. In particular, we will walk through data preprocessing, data cleaning, summary statistics, and using a machine learning model to capture potential relationships. Given metadata about a potential game, our model aims to predict its level of success as measured by how many copies are sold.

In particular, it will be interesting to see whether our model can verify the general idea that gameplay determines a game's success the most by failing to find important relationships. This would mean success is not tied to metadata. However, it may also fail to disprove our intuition by being very accurate, meaning relationships were found.

We also would like our model to highlight what it deems to be the most important factor in determining a games' success.

Data Curation

We took a Steam game dataset that already scraped data from the Steam and SteamSpy APIs. SteamSpy is a site that tracks and analyzes Steam sales, so we will train our model on estimates since Steam doesn't release the exact number of sales a game has.

First, we import all of the libraries we plan on using.

For ease of access, we will import the CSV as a Pandas DataFrame, and operate on that.

As you can see, we are working with 27,000 games. Each game has the following features:

  • appid: the unique application identifier for each game
  • name: the name of the game
  • release_date: when the game was released in YYYY-MM-DD format
  • english: whether the game is in English (1 if yes, 0 if no)
  • developer: the name(s) of the developer(s). The developer creates and owns the game
  • publisher: the name(s) of the publisher(s). The publisher markets the game
  • platforms: which platforms are supported by the game (ie: operating system)
  • required age: the minimum required age according to PEGI UK standards
  • categories: list of game categories (ie: functionality)
  • genres: list of game genres (ie: gameplay)
  • steamspy_tags: list of game tags. This is similar to genres but is community-voted
  • achievements: number of in-game achievements
  • positive_ratings: the number of positive ratings. Note that ratings are either positive or negative
  • negative_ratings: the number of negative ratings
  • average_playtime: the average user playtime
  • median_playtime: the median user playtime
  • owners: estimated number of game owners
  • price: current price of the game in GBP

It seems that the majority of the games are in English and have no PEGI UK age rating. Also, it seems that over half of the games don't have achievements. As there are several games in the list who do in fact have achievements despite being listed as not, this is likely an error in the dataset. Genres are also fairly redundant, as many of them are already contained in the tags. The appid and name for each game isn't necessary for analysis, as the other data points are more important. Because of this, let's drop these six columns.

In[]:
df = df.drop(columns=["appid", "english", "required_age", "genres", "achievements", "name"])

We also have several semicolon-separated lists in our dataset, namely the "steamspy_tags", "categories", and "platforms" columns. It will be easier to handle them as lists, so we'll go ahead and convert them. The sales column also can be converted to a list of min-max.

In[]:
# convert sales to a list of min-max
df['sales'] = df['sales'].apply(lambda x: x.split("-"))

# convert steamspy tags to a list
df["steamspy_tags"] = df["steamspy_tags"].apply(lambda x: x.split(";"))

# convert categories to a list
df["categories"] = df["categories"].apply(lambda x: x.split(";"))

# convert platforms to a list and capitalize the first letter of each element
def convert_platforms(entry):
    entry_list = entry.split(";")
    return [e.capitalize() for e in entry_list]

df["platforms"] = df["platforms"].apply(convert_platforms)

Depending on a game's popularity, it may have more or less reviews than other games. There is no "total ratings" column, so let's add that. Additionally, to better see the ratio between positive and negative reviews, let's calculate that and put it into a "positive rating proportion" column.

In[]:
# calculate total ratings
df["total_ratings"] = df["positive_ratings"] + df["negative_ratings"]

# calculate positive rating proportion by dividing positive ratings over the total number of ratings
df["pos_rating_proportion"] = df['positive_ratings']/(df['negative_ratings']+df['positive_ratings'])
df['pos_rating_proportion_categories'] = df["pos_rating_proportion"].apply(lambda x: str( ((x//0.1)*10)) + "% to " + str((x//0.1)*10+10) + "%" )

Since the number of sales is a range, let's create "maximum sales" and "minimum sales" columns so we can work with the numbers.

In[]:
df["minimum_sales"] = df["sales"].apply(lambda x: int(x[0]))
df["maximum_sales"] = df["sales"].apply(lambda x: int(x[1]))

We will also make a copy of our dataframe, so we have an unchanged original copy and a new copy in which we can perform transformations on. This is nice, as we will perform many different transformations for our ML model that can appear cluttered.

In[]:
# make a copy of df for the model, since it's easier to do data analysis on a list but one-hot encode for a model
df2 = df.copy(deep=True)

Exploratory Data Analysis

We can analyze the dataset in many ways, especially with how many columns we have. We chose to analyze the publishers' positive rating proportions, price category vs sales, and median playtime vs positive rating proportion.

Summary Stat 1 (ANOVA)

Let's analyze the game publisher's positive rating proportions. Since the publisher is a categorical variable, and the mean rating proportion is continuous, we can use an ANOVA test to see if the difference in means is significant.

We will have the following hypotheses:

  • H0: there is no statistically significant difference between top Steam game publishers' mean positive rating proportions
  • HA: there is a statistically significant difference between top Steam game publishers' mean positive rating proportions

First, let's see how many publisher's we're working with.

In[]:
print("Number of unique publishers: {}".format(len(df2["publisher"].value_counts())))

Number of unique publishers: 14351

14,000 publishers is a lot to do an ANOVA test on. Let's see how the publishers are distributed among total sales.

In[]:
# Group sales by publisher, sum them, and sort them from greatest to least

print("Number of publishers with sales > 50,000: {}".format(publisher_sales[publisher_sales >= 50000].size))
print("Number of publishers with sales > 1,000,000: {}".format(publisher_sales[publisher_sales >= 1000000].size))

Number of publishers with sales > 50,000: 2555

Let's do an ANOVA test on the top 9 publishers.

In[]:
# find the names of the top 20 publishers who have the most sales
top_9_publishers_names = publisher_sales.head(9).index

# get the respective rating proportion groups for each publisher
grouped_proportions = df2["pos_rating_proportion"].groupby(df2["publisher"])
top_9_groups = [group for name, group in grouped_proportions if name in top_9_publishers_names]

# ANOVA test
print("P-value: {}".format(scipy.stats.f_oneway(*top_9_groups)[1]))

P-value: 2.269163519775008e-06

Let's also plot the mean rating proportions to get a better understanding of the difference between the publishers.

In[]:
# get the mean of the group proportions and filter by the top publishers
grouped_proportions.mean().filter(items=top_9_publishers_names).sort_values(ascending=False).plot(kind="bar", ylabel = "positive rating proportion")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.yticks([0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1])
plt.title("Mean Positive Rating Proportion for Top 20 Publishers by Sales") 
plt.show()

Since the p-value is below the significance value of 0.05, we can conclude that there is a statistically significant difference between the top 9 Steam game publishers' mean positive rating proportions. This suggests that while all 9 publishers have a large player base, not all of the publishers have the same ratings for their franchises. This means that the name of the publisher matters when it comes to the average rating of a game. We were interested in testing this hypothesis because we wanted to see whether certain publishers had generally higher percentage of positive game reviews than others. This test tells us that we need to incorporate the publisher into our predictive ML model.

Summary Stat 2 (Chi-Squared)

Next, let's find the ratio of price category to category of success measured by number of sales.

  • H0: there is no correlation between percentage of positive ratings a game has and how many sales it has

  • HA: there is a correlation between the percentage of positive ratings a game has and how many sales it has

Since the price data can be broken down into reasonable quantiles, we can create categories using them.

In[]:
def split_price_categories(price):
    if price <= 0.79:
        return "Low"
    elif price <= 3.19:
        return "Medium-Low"
    elif price <= 5.19:
        return "Medium"
    elif price <= 9.29:
        return "Medium-High"
    else:
        return "High"
    
df2["price_categories"] = df2['price'].apply(split_price_categories)

In this step, instead of dealing with a numerical range for the sales, we convert each to a category. This will be helpful for our ML model later.

Sales categories:

  • 0-50,000 -> Low
  • 50,000-200,000 -> Medium-Low
  • 200,000-2,000,000 -> Medium
  • 2,000,000-20,000,000 -> Medium-High
  • 20,000,000+ -> High

A similar conversion is performed over the price for each game.

In[]:
def split_sales_categories(numsales):
    if numsales == 0 or numsales == 20000:
        return "Low"
    elif numsales == 50000 or numsales == 100000:
        return "Medium-Low"
    elif numsales == 200000 or numsales == 500000 or numsales== 1000000:
        return "Medium"
    elif numsales == 2000000 or numsales == 5000000 or numsales == 10000000:
        return "Medium-High"
    else:
        return "High"

df2["sales_categories"] = df2['minimum_sales'].apply(split_sales_categories)

We are interested in this conclusion since we wanted to see how pricing of a game impacts how successful it will be as measured by total sales

Summary Stat 3 (Pearson Correlation Coefficient)

Finally, we will use Pearson Correlation to find if there is a correlation between the median playtime of the game and its positive rating proportion.

In[]:
# find correlation between median playtime and pos rating proportion using pearson correlation

correlation_coefficient = df2['median_playtime'].corr(df2['pos_rating_proportion'])

plt.scatter(df2['median_playtime'], df2['pos_rating_proportion'], alpha=0.5)
plt.xlabel('Median Playtime')
plt.ylabel('Positive Ratings Proportion')
plt.title(f'Median Playtime vs. Positive Ratings Proportion (Correlation Coefficient: {correlation_coefficient:.2f})')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

print("Pearson Correlation Coefficient (r):" , correlation_coefficient)

Pearson Correlation Coefficient (r): 0.013231710785338947

For this test, we wanted to see if there was possibly a correlation between the positive reception of a game and its median playtime. As a base assumption, we assumed that a better reception would lead to more hours and a worse reception less hours. This would make sense, as a more quality game can lead to people wanting to play it more. As the graph/coefficient shows, there is little correlation between them. The Pearson correlation coefficient test was chosen as it nicely highlights the correlation (or lack thereof) between the two variables.

Data Analysis Conclusions

From our first test, we can conclude that there is a statistically significant difference between the top 5 Steam game publishers' mean positive rating proportions. For our algorithm, we want to include the publisher name in our ML model.

From our second test, we can conclude that there is a relationship between the price category of a game and its number of sales. (Using graph, we see that the highest sales categories present most in games with high)

From our third test, we can conclude that the reception of a game does not necessarily impact its median playtime. For our algorithm, we can make the playtime of a game have less weight in determining its reception.

Primary Analysis: Machine Learning Model

Now for our model.

As we explained before, we want to use a classification model to predict a Steam game's sales. For this project, we choose to use an ensemble of decision trees. To make this process easier, we are using a framework developed by Microsoft called LightGBM. We choose this specifically since it has better support for categorical features than scikitlearn or XGBoost.

Now our data as is isn't compatible with training (lists, non-ascii characters, etc.), so we need to do some cleaning. After cleaning, we perform One Hot Encoding on the platforms, categories, and tags by splitting apart their respective lists. This step really fattens up our dataframe!

In[]:
# replace all non-ASCII strings with "Other". This doesnt make a difference since we don't care about the publisher's exact name.
def clean_ascii(x):
    np.set_printoptions(threshold=sys.maxsize)
    if (not str(x).isascii()):
        return "Other"
    return x

# replace all JSON special characters with "_"
def rid_json(x):
    return re.sub('[^A-Za-z0-9_]+', '_', str(x))

# apply both functions to publisher and developer columns
df2["publisher"] = df2["publisher"].apply(clean_ascii)
df2["developer"] = df2["developer"].apply(clean_ascii)
df2["publisher"] = df2["publisher"].apply(rid_json)
df2["developer"] = df2["developer"].apply(rid_json)

# manually apply "Category" and "Tag" prefix to category and tag columns since
# one hot encoding doesn't automatically parse semi-colon-separated lists
df2["categories"] = df2["categories"].apply(lambda x: ["Category " + str(y) for y in x])
df2["steamspy_tags"] = df2["steamspy_tags"].apply(lambda x: ["Tag " + str(y) for y in x])

# perform one-hot encoding on platforms, categories, and steamspy_tags columns
df2 = (df2.join(df2.pop('platforms')
              .apply('|'.join)
              .str.get_dummies())
      )
df2 = (df2.join(df2.pop('categories')
              .apply('|'.join)
              .str.get_dummies())
      )
df2 = (df2.join(df2.pop('steamspy_tags')
              .apply('|'.join)
              .str.get_dummies())
      )
df2

Because we are trying to predict categorical data with LightGBM, we must first translate each category to a number.

Then we perform a standard train/test split to get our training and test sets.

In[]:
y = df2['sales_categories'].copy(deep=True).map({"Low": 0, "Medium-Low": 1, "Medium": 2, "Medium-High": 3, "High": 4})

X = df2.iloc[:, 1:]
X = X.drop(columns=["sales_categories"])

X[['average_playtime', 'median_playtime', "price", "pos_rating_proportion", "total_ratings"]] = StandardScaler().fit_transform(df2[['average_playtime', 
                                                                                                                                    'median_playtime', 
                                                                                                                                    "price", 
                                                                                                                                    "pos_rating_proportion", 
                                                                                                                                    "total_ratings"]])

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 0)

Now for the actual training!

As mentioned earlier, we chose LightGBM for our model as it has a fairly robust set of features, including allowing for categorical features and using an ensemble tecnique called gradient boosting by default. It's also dead simple to use and train with, not requiring much tuning.

For LightGBM, we must provide parameters that specify how we want our model to train.

In[]:
PARAMS = {
    "objective": "multiclass", # we have multiple categories we're trying to predict
    "num_class": 5, # specifically, 5 classes
    "num_iterations": 500,
    "learning_rate": 0.05,
    "num_leaves": 2048, # specify maximum number of leaves in the model
    "max_depth": 15, # specify maximum model depth
    "min_data_in_leaf": 50,
    "verbose": -1,
}

x_train = lgb.Dataset(X_train, y_train)
model = lgb.train(PARAMS, x_train)

Now that our model has finished training, let's print out its classification report!

The predict function returns the probabilities for each category, so we can take the highest one as the categorical prediction.

Wow. Those sure do look glorious. Seaborn for the win!

These new plots we are using are violin plots. Essentially, they allow us to see a box and whisker distribution and density curves for all the data that falls into a certain category, adding another layer of dimensionality to the data. Where you see total ratings going below -1 or % pos ratings go above 1.0 is an artifact of the violin plot

Now, let's take a second to analyze these results and see why they make sense, and why our model chose them as the more important features.

In our first plot of total ratings per sales category, we see that games with more ratings tend to have a higher sales category. This makes sense: the more people who buy a game, the more users who can/do leave a review.

Our second plot of % of positive reviews per sales category shows something interesting. Although the medians for all categories for % positive ratings are very pretty similar, the higher sales categories seem to have slightly higher maximum percentages and it seems like most of the data is closer to the upper end of the percentage scale. Although a human might miss these miniscule differences, the model is able to use these fluctuations differences to make an informed decision. Once again, this makes sense: games with higher percentages of positive ratings means people liked the game, and therefore it would make sense that this feature has a high importance in determining overall success.

Our third and fourth plots show the median and average playtime per sales category respectively. Intuitively, you would expect games with a higher playtime to be more popular, but at first look, the plots seem to show that games with medium or medium low sales have the most amount of playtime. This is where the violin plot shines! We can look at the distribution (density) of the data in each category and see that the games in the high sales category have less outliers and a greater density towards the maximum of the distribution. Once again, this makes sense: games with higher playtimes means people liked the game, and therefore it would make sense that this feature has a high importance in determining overall success.

Our final plot, price versus sales category, also shows something interesting. It looks like games that have high sales have a lower median than the rest. In the context of the tree, it makes sense that price is an important feature to determining sales since cheaper games are more affordable to players.

Phew. That was a lot. Now that we understand why our ensemble chose these categories, time to visualize our decision tree in all its glory!

Insights and Conclusions

One of the main things that we noticed from our model is that it is very good at predicting the "Low", "Medium", and "High" prices, but is pretty bad at predicting the categories between them. This is an interesting observation. One reason we think this may be the case is that the values for the intermediary categories are more similar to each other than the categories on the edge. So, it would have a harder time distinguishing between the intermediary cases.

Our model's accuracy also supports our hypothesis that there are indeed factors that have an impact on how many copies of a game are sold. Based on the feature importance within our model, it seems that the total number of ratings and the positive rating proportion have the largest impact on the number of owners. This makes sense, as a game with more reviews most likely means that it has been purchased more. A higher positivity percentage combined with the number of total ratings would also imply that potential buyers would be more willing to purchase, as the game is highly reviewed by many people.

To use our model for new games, we would have to manually put in dummy values for reviews or playtime to simulate a game being on the store. An example of these values could be the median or means of those features. Another follow-up project could try creating a model while dropping these features from the dataset to see if sales can still be predicted accurately.

Since the data was also scraped around May 2019, it would be interesting to see if the model is still accurate when assessing newer games. It would be interesting to see how the model assesses groundbreaking games such as Elden Ring, Baldur's Gate 3, Lethal Company, or Helldivers 2.

As for the process as a whole, one key takeaway is the importance of data analysis and cleaning. At the start, our dataframe wasn't easy to work with, so transforming the data into a nicer format was a necessary change. Certain parts of the dataframe were difficult to work with, such as the semicolon separated list, showing the impact data collection can have on data analysis. It's good to keep in mind what you want to do with the data you collect before actually gathering it to prevent more work down the line.
